  "prompt": "In what grade do American students learn topics like integral, derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves in detail?",
  "response": "In the American education system, the specific grade levels at which students learn topics like integrals, derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves can vary depending on the school, district, and individual student progression, but generally, these topics are covered at the following levels:\n\n1. **Calculus (Integrals and Derivatives):** \n   - Integrals and derivatives are typically introduced in a Calculus course, which many students take during their 11th or 12th grade in high school, especially if they are on an advanced mathematics track. Some students might take it earlier if they are ahead in mathematics.\n   - Advanced Placement (AP) Calculus AB and BC courses, which include these topics, are commonly taken by juniors or seniors.\n\n2. **Organic Chemistry:**\n   - Organic chemistry is usually a more advanced topic not typically covered in detail until college. However, some high schools offer Advanced Placement (AP) or International Baccalaureate (IB) Chemistry courses that might include an introduction to organic chemistry topics in the 11th or 12th grade.\n\n3. **Waves:**\n   - The study of waves is usually part of a physics curriculum. Basic concepts related to waves are introduced in general high school physics courses, which students often take in 11th grade. \n   - More detailed study might occur in an AP Physics course, such as AP Physics 1 or AP Physics C, usually taken in 11th or 12th grade.\n\nThese topics are often explored further in college courses for students pursuing science, technology, engineering, or mathematics (STEM) fields.",
